                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d271">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11 Changsha/10: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-12-09T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 9, 1930—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>424. Your 1025 of December 2, 4 p.m.<note n="24" xml:id="d271fn24">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>If in your further discussion of the Changsha incident with the Chinese
                        authorities it should appear that there is a possibility that such claims
                        may be treated as were the Nanking claims, you may state that the Department
                        would be willing to accept a similar arrangement for the adjudication of the
                        Changsha claims.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Please keep Department informed promptly with regard to developments and
                        any steps that are being or may be taken by other foreign
                        governments.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
